<b><a href="/wiki/Meat" title="Meat">Meat</a></b></td>
</tr>
<tr>
<th style="text-align: left; font-weight: normal;"><b>Variations:</b></th>
<td>Multiple</td>
</tr>
</table>
<p><b>Chili con carne</b> (literally "Chili with meat", often known simply as <b>chili</b>) is a <a href="/wiki/Spice" title="Spice">spicy</a> <a href="/wiki/Stew" title="Stew">stew</a> made from <a href="/wiki/Chili_pepper" title="Chili pepper">chili peppers</a>, <a href="/wiki/Meat" title="Meat">meat</a>, <a href="/wiki/Garlic" title="Garlic">garlic</a>, <a href="/wiki/Onion" title="Onion">onions</a>, and <a href="/wiki/Cumin" title="Cumin">cumin</a>. Traditional chili is made with chopped or ground beef. Variations, either geographic or by personal preference, may substitute different types of meat and may also include <a href="/wiki/Tomato" title="Tomato">tomatoes</a>, <a href="/wiki/Beans" title="Beans" class="mw-redirect">beans</a>, or other ingredients. The name "chili con carne" is a variation of the <a href="/wiki/Spanish_language" title="Spanish language">Spanish</a> <i>chile con carne</i>, which means "peppers with meat." Chili con carne is the official dish of the <a href="/wiki/U.S._state" title="U.S. state">U.S. state</a> of <a href="/wiki/Texas" title="Texas">Texas</a>. It can be found worldwide in local variations and also in certain American-style fast food restaurants.</p>
